<h2>20th August</h2>
<p class="au">Prof. Tim Stapleton (Trent University)</p>
<p class="ti">African police and soldiers in colonial Southern 
Rhodesia (Zimbabwe) 1890-1980</p>
<p class="when">(5.00 pm Faculty Committee Room)</p>

<h2>3rd September</h2>
<p class="au">Prof. Part Mgadla (History Department)</p>
<p class="ti">Of Capital towns and boundaries: Vryburg, Mafikeng, Gaborone and
Molopo/Ramatlabama boundary: 1885-1965</p>
<p class="when">(5.00 pm Faculty Committee Room)</p>

<h2>10th September</h2>
<p class="au">Dr. Ceri Ashley (University College, London)</p>
<p class="ti">The archaeology of Khwebe Hills: exploring the 
impact of migration</p>
<p class="when">(5.00 pm Faculty Committee Room)</p>

<h2>17th September</h2>
<p class="au">Mrs. Nonofho Ndobochani (Archaeology Unit, 
History Department)</p>
<p class="ti">Graduate seminar</p>
<p class="when">(5.00 pm Faculty Committee Room)</p>

<h2>8th October</h2>
<p class="au">Dr. Bruce Bennett (History Department)</p>
<p class="ti">"To do <i>what</i>?": the Establishment activism of Archbishop Randall
Davidson</p>
<p class="when">(5.00 pm Faculty Committee Room)</p>

<h2>15th October</h2>
<p class="au">All graduate students</p>
<p class="ti">Graduate seminar</p>
<p class="when">(5.00 pm Faculty Committee Room)</p>

<h2>22nd October</h2>
<p class="au">Dr. Wazha Morapedi (History Department)</p>
<p class="ti">The dilemmas of liberation in Southern Africa: the case of Botswana and the
Zimbabwean liberation movements, 1960-1980</p>
<p class="when">(5.00 pm Faculty Committee Room)</p>

<h2>29th October</h2>
<p class="au">Dr. Sarah Mothulatshipi (Archaeology Unit, 
History Department)</p>
<p class="ti">The archaeology of Mothudi site, Eastern Botswana: 
preliminary results from a recent field survey</p>
<p class="when">(5.00 pm Faculty Committee Room)</p>

<h2>5th November</h2>
<p class="au">Prof. Fred Morton (The Botswana Society)</p>
<p class="ti">When historical narratives began to appear: oral 
traditions in the Western Transvaal
and Eastern Botswana since 1900.</p>
<p class="when">(5.00 pm Faculty Committee Room)</p>

<h2>12th November</h2>
<p class="au">Prof. Ackson Kanduza (History Department)</p>
